#Text=CHAPTER I
#Text=[ The Knighted Knave of Bergen ]
#Text=One day it occurred to me that it had been many years since the world had been afforded the spectacle of a man adventurous enough to undertake a journey through Europe on foot .
#Text=After much thought , I decided that I was a person fitted to furnish to mankind this spectacle .
#Text=So I determined to do it .
#Text=This was in March , 1878 .
#Text=I looked about me for the right sort of person to accompany me in the capacity of agent , and finally hired a Mr. Harris for this service .
#Text=It was also my purpose to study art while in Europe .
#Text=Mr. Harris was in sympathy with me in this .
#Text=He was as much of an enthusiast in art as I was , and not less anxious to learn to paint .
#Text=I desired to learn the German language ; so did Harris .
#Text=Toward the middle of April we sailed in the HOLSATIA , Captain Brandt , and had a very pleasant trip , indeed .

#Text=After a brief rest at Hamburg , we made preparations for a long pedestrian trip southward in the soft spring weather , but at the last moment we changed the program , for private reasons , and took the express-train .
#Text=We made a short halt at Frankfort-on-the-Main , and found it an interesting city .
#Text=I would have liked to visit the birthplace of Gutenburg , but it could not be done , as no memorandum of the site of the house has been kept .
#Text=So we spent an hour in the Goethe mansion instead .
#Text=The city permits this house to belong to private parties , instead of gracing and dignifying herself with the honor of possessing and protecting it .
#Text=Frankfort is one of the sixteen cities which have the distinction of being the place where the following incident occurred .
#Text=Charlemagne , while chasing the Saxons ( as HE said ) , or being chased by them ( as THEY said ) , arrived at the bank of the river at dawn , in a fog .
#Text=The enemy were either before him or behind him ; but in any case he wanted to get across , very badly .
#Text=He would have given anything for a guide , but none was to be had .
#Text=Presently he saw a deer , followed by her young , approach the water .
#Text=He watched her , judging that she would seek a ford , and he was right .
#Text=She waded over , and the army followed .

#Text=So a great Frankish victory or defeat was gained or avoided ; and in order to commemorate the episode , Charlemagne commanded a city to be built there , which he named Frankfort -- the ford of the Franks .
#Text=None of the other cities where this event happened were named for it .
#Text=This is good evidence that Frankfort was the first place it occurred at .
#Text=Frankfort has another distinction -- it is the birthplace of the German alphabet ; or at least of the German word for alphabet -- BUCHSTABEN .
#Text=They say that the first movable types were made on birch sticks -- BUCHSTABE -- hence the name .
#Text=I was taught a lesson in political economy in Frankfort .
#Text=I had brought from home a box containing a thousand very cheap cigars .
#Text=By way of experiment , I stepped into a little shop in a queer old back street , took four gaily decorated boxes of wax matches and three cigars , and laid down a silver piece worth 48 cents .
#Text=The man gave me 43 cents change .
#Text=In Frankfort everybody wears clean clothes , and I think we noticed that this strange thing was the case in Hamburg , too , and in the villages along the road .
#Text=Even in the narrowest and poorest and most ancient quarters of Frankfort neat and clean clothes were the rule .
#Text=The little children of both sexes were nearly always nice enough to take into a body 's lap .
#Text=And as for the uniforms of the soldiers , they were newness and brightness carried to perfection .
#Text=One could never detect a smirch or a grain of dust upon them .
#Text=The street-car conductors and drivers wore pretty uniforms which seemed to be just out of the bandbox , and their manners were as fine as their clothes .
